training_organizations.name: Maryland Child Welfare Training Academy (UM SSW)
training_organizations.description: A training academy operated through the University of Maryland School of Social Work in partnership with the Maryland Department of Human Services. It prepares child welfare workers (from Maryland’s state-supervised, county-administered system) via pre-service training, and offers ongoing courses. The academy emphasizes Maryland’s integrated practice model, trauma-informed care, and family engagement techniques.

training_organizations.name: Pressley Ridge
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit treatment and foster care agency that contracts with Maryland’s local departments of social services to serve children with higher needs:contentReference[oaicite:23]{index=23}. Pressley Ridge provides specialized foster homes (therapeutic foster care), operates residential programs, and offers reunification services. Maryland places children with Pressley Ridge when they require intensive support, and the agency works toward stabilizing placements and achieving permanency.

training_organizations.name: Building Families for Children (Maryland)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit organization in Maryland that provides foster care and family support services under contract. It recruits foster families (including for therapeutic foster care), provides training and support to those families, and offers services like parent mentoring and community resource linkage to birth families – all in coordination with Maryland’s county child welfare agencies:contentReference[oaicite:24]{index=24}.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.DecentralScreen: Each county/region has own screening unit
policies.ReportAnonymous: General public (not mandated reporters) can remain anonymous
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Abuse includes physical injury and sexual abuse; Sexual abuse includes sexual trafficking; Mental injury is a subtype of both abuse and neglect
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes failure to provide proper care and attention, malnourishment, inadequate clothing, inadequate shelter, and medical neglect; Mental injury is a subtype of both abuse and neglect
policies.Exempt_OtherSpecify: Physical injury of a child by accidental means
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Penalty_OtherSpecify: Fine up to $10,000; Complaint filed with the appropriate licensing board, county board of education, or the appropriate agency, institution, or license facility at which the person is employed
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Parental screening for substance use and domestic violence
policies.ScreenReq_OtherSpecify: Review of sex offender registry and Maryland Judiciary Case search; Complete Child Abuse/Neglect screening and response time assessment; Check history on Department of Juvenile Services dashboard
policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: Collateral contact; The general condition, emotional and physical state, and proximity to threat of all children; The family's likely level of cooperation or overall receptivity to accepting agency intervention or assistance; Any potential danger to an investigating worker
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: Any individual can be a perpetrator of sex trafficking; For neglect, a perpetrator can only be a parent, guardian, or caregiver of the alleged victim
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: The agencies responsible for investigating reported cases of suspected sexual abuse, including the local department, the appropriate law enforcement agencies, and the local State's Attorney, have a joint investigation procedure for conducting joint investigations of sexual abuse, which includes ongoing training program for personnel involved in the investigation or prosecution of sexual abuse cases
policies.CaseManagerQual_OtherSpecify: Licensed as a Graduate Social Worker (on or by June 30, 2018), Master Social Worker (on or after July 1, 2018), Certified Social Worker or Certified Social Worker-Clinical
policies.InvestReq_OtherCases_Specify: Required if the initial referral indicates that parental substance use or intimate partner violence is impacting the safety of children in the home
policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: Screeners must be properly trained on Structured Decision Making (SDM) or, screening practices aligned with Family-Centered Practices, and apply screening policies that allow screeners to obtain the most comprehensive and complete information possible to inform decision making and subsequent agency actions
policies.InvestReq_MHEvalCases_Specify: If mental injury is suspected, an assessment by two of the following: (1) a licensed physician, (2) a licensed psychologist, or (3) a licensed social worker
policies.ScreenerQual_ExperienceSpecify: Some screening positions require one year of experience, other do not require any
policies.AltResp_EligibilityMaltreatment: Only certain types of maltreatment are eligible
policies.CaseManagerQual_TrainingSpecify: Must complete an approved training program and pass a competency test before being granted permanent employment status; Meet mandatory standards for continuing education
policies.ExtFosterCare_Reentry_OtherSpec: Have not yet reached the age of 20 years 6 months; Youth cannot have exited foster care due to reunification, adoption, guardianship, marriage, or military duty; Comply with the voluntary placement agreement; Youth must agree to same criteria as youth to remain in extended foster care
policies.AltResp_Eligibility_OtherSpecify: A reassessment of the report or relevant facts that demonstrate that the case meets the criteria for an Alternative Response and a determination that accepted services would address all issues of risk of abuse or neglect and child safety
policies.InvestReq_HomeStudyCases_Specify: Physical or sexual abuse; Neglect; Mental injury
